NINE people, including prominent businessman Lucas Mallya were on Wednesday arraigned over evasion allegations. They appeared before the Kisutu Resident Magistrate’s Court in Dar es Salaam charged with evading tax of over 3 1bn/ -, among other 28 charges of transactions relating to tax receipts and hard drinks importation. Other accused persons are businessmen Emmanuel V icent, Prochesi Shayo, Prokolini Shayo, Geofrey Urio, Nyasulu Kyapi and Happy Mwamugunda, a businesswoman as well as Nelson Kahangwa and Tunsubilege Mateni, both accountants. Other charges include leading organised crime, forgery, being in possession of stamps printed without authority, occasioning loss to a specified authority, importation of goods without being registered, distribution of excisable goods without fixing stamps and money laundering. They were not allowed to enter plea to the charges before Senior Resident Magistrate Godfrey Isaya because they fall under the Economic and Organised Crime Control Act. The case was adjourned to February 12, 2020, as investigations are incomplete. Prosecuting, Principal State Attorney Zacharia Ndascoy and State Attorney Faraji Nguka told the court that on diverse dates between January 1, 2015 and January 7, 2020 in Dar es Salaam and other places within the United Republic of Tanzania, all accused intentionally organised a criminal racket. On or before June 3 , 2019 in the city, with intent to defraud, Mallya, a Director with Jaluma General Supplies Limited, allegedly forged electronic tax stamps, showing that were made by the Tanzania Revenue Authority (TRA) and on the same day he uttered them to the Authority, purporting that they were genuine, the fact he knew was false. The prosecution alleged that on January 7, 2020 at Chang’ombe A in Temeke District in the city, the businessman was found in possession of 93 rolls of the stamps valued at 80,516 ,000/ - printed without the authority of the Commissioner. Between January 1, 2016 and December 3 1, 2019 in Dar es Salaam by reasons of his willful acts of making counterfeit stamps, Mallya allegedly caused the government of Tanzania to suffer pecuniary loss of 15,241,075,16 9/ - and within the same period fraudulently evaded payment of the sum as tax to TRA. The Director of Jaluma General Supplies Limited was charged with money laundering in that within the same period in the city, he allegedly acquired the sum of 15bn/ -, while he knew or ought to have known that the amount was proceeds of a predicate offence of fraudulent tax evasion. On January 3 , 2020 at Mbezi Makabe area in Dar es Salaam, Vincent was allegedly found in possession of four rolls of stamps, each containing 6 ,000 stamps amounting to 24,000 stamps, all valued at 1,104,000/ -, printed without the authority of Commissioner. The prosecution alleged that without being registered with the Commissioner, Mwamugunda, who is the Director with Happy Imports Associates imported excisable goods, which are 413 cartons of Drostdy Hof Wine, valued at 24,780,000/ - between January 1, 2017 and December 3 1, 2019. Within the same period in the city, with intent to evade tax, the businesswoman allegedly imported the 413 cartons of the said unregistered excisable goods, thereby evading payment of 9,584,401,3 93 / - as excise duty and V alue Added Tax (V AT) payable to TRA. It was alleged that within the same period in Dar es Salaam, by reasons of her willful acts of importing and distributing the goods without being licensed and upon affixing electronic counterfeit stamps, Mwamugunda caused the government of Tanzania to suffer pecuniary loss of the said 9.5bn/ -. The businesswoman was also charged with money laundering in that with the same period in the city she acquired 9,584,401,3 93 / - , while she knew or ought to have known that the amount was proceeds of predicate offence of fraudulent evasion of tax. On or before December 19, 2019 at Tabata area in the city, the two Shayo brothers allegedly distributed excised goods without affixing stamps, which are several cartons of hard drinks, Robertson Wine, Drostdy Hof, Cousins and Amarula, all valued at 13 9,03 2,000/ -.